segments.text: If you had total authority, how organizationally would you place TTI?
Well, TTI, I'm unbiased in this question because I've always fought to have TTI recognized as a part of the system, just like other parts of the system, T's, Ag Experiment Station, those.
In reporting through some manner to the chancellor's office.
We have gone the other direction.
I think that there have been proposals to put some of the system parts back under the university.
I think that the system has grown so big now that that's not a feasible solution.
It's not feasible to put them back under.
Back under a university because it seems to me we've always had the problem of who is really running this ship?
Is this a system run by the president of the university or is it a system run by a system chancellor with presidents and directors of agencies?
And I know that while organizationally on the chart,
TTI with its little bitty operation is basically the equivalent of the university.
Everybody, including us, know that's not so.
We are not first among equals.
We are the last among equals in that regard.
But we don't have the same kind of problems.
And they don't need to all be addressed the same way.
Is there any advice that you would give to TTI today for the future if you were hired as its consultant?
Yeah, the first thing I'd say is let's not try to follow all of the guidelines of the issue we were just talking about, and that is of recruiting people.
Let's try to identify the people that we think we really would like to have for the purposes that we want to have those people here.

get the best people we can and not go through the torturing process that makes it so difficult to get a decision for them that they yes they would really like to come here and go through all this process or secondly that we have end up with people who are average and that's all and uh if we can if we can stay out of that the best way we can
and stay out of the courthouse, I think we'll be miles ahead.
OK.
I've just about finished the questions I could think of.
What have we left out that we should have included?
I think it's been pretty thorough.
You've asked me more than I can respond to, I think, what it is.
So concluding questions that I ask everybody.
What has it meant to you that you attended Texas A&M?
Well, I don't think I would have been nearly as successful in any endeavor that I went into had I not attended Texas A&M.
I think A&M was a good crucible that allowed me to try to get an education that I could make

use of and would give me some benefits of trying to deal with the difficult problems that I'm going to have to face what's going to have to face in the future of my career and I think A&M has meant more than just to my ability to make a living coming here it's I think the whole process of having pride in an institution

is uh is worth a great deal if you can't go to a place and spend your life and then say hey this was a great place to be you started out in the wrong place i think i think a m has done it not only for me but i think it's done that same thing for others as well all right next the last question somebody walks up to you and hands you a check for a million dollars with one condition
You have to pass it on to Texas A&M.
You can define Texas A&M however you want to.
And the only condition is you've got to pass it on, but you get to decide what they do with it.
What would you tell them to do with your big gift?
Well, I've not really faced that problem yet.
Let me think about that just a moment.
One thing that I think we need

to do with it, and a million dollars is not going to solve the problem, but it would help a whole lot, is that we need to have some funds available to award promising young faculty that we think we can identify that are going to be the stars in 15 years from now.
in this organization to be sure that they're not bled away from us because we can't do something for them to convince them to stay here.
And I think that if we can get the right people and keep the right people, there's no end of what we can do.
But that, I think, is a real difficult thing for us to do is to
continue to be able to do that.
I think we've been very fortunate in the past and been able to keep a bunch of people that had better opportunity or more financially better opportunities than a lot of other places.
I think that might be the first place I'd put it.
Last question.
What feelings do you carry in your heart for Texas A&M now?
Very good.
Great feelings for A&M.
I thought it's
of all it's done and for the opportunities that it has to continue to be a, a major part.
And I think that I've got hopes that that's even going to be more rather than less in the future.

As we, one of the things that growth, although I'm not a real growth proponent, but growth has brought us, it's brought us visibility in the sense that, uh, we are now one of the two flagship universities in the state.
And, uh,
For most of my views, we may be the leading flagship university in the state because of the different things that we do and do quite well.
Now, I know we're not ranked as high out of many of our academic departments as University of Texas is, but I think that there's a whole lot of inertia in that process as well.
Let's quit there.
